<p><lb 
n="1"/><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">siddhaM| catur-udadhi-salilāsvāditayaśaso mahārājādhirāja-śrī-kumāraguptasya</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">sa</supplied>mvatsara-śa<unclear reason="illegible">te</unclear> trayodaśotta<!-- 
daba: I adopt Sircar's conjecture for the beginning except hypothesising siddham instead of his oṁ. 
--><lb 
n="2" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">re</supplied> <gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="23" unit="character"/><!-- 
daba: Sircar's conjecture for the beginning of this line is saṁ 100+10+3 (after re, I guess, though he may have read re at the end of the first line - which I consider very unlikely) 
--></p>
<p><supplied reason="lost">asyā</supplied><sic>n</sic> d<unclear>i</unclear>vasa-pūrvvāyāṁ parama-daivata-para<lb 
n="3" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">ma-bhaṭṭāraka-</supplied><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">mahārājādhirāja-śrī-kumāragupte pr̥thivīpatau</supplied> kuṭu<unclear>mbi</unclear> <gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="3" unit="character"/> brāhmaṇa-śivaśarmma-nāgaśarmma-maha<!-- 
daba: The conjectural filling-up is from Lielukhine, i.e. probably Sircar. Compare the Damodarpur plates. Bhandarkar reads ā(?) before kuṭumbi, I see nothing (not even kuṭumbi), but this could be part of an au mātrā. The broken-off gap after kuṭumbi is 2 or 3 characters in size, but I can't make out brāhmaṇa either on the facsimile, nor anything else really, except what may be śi of śivaśarmma. 
--><lb 
n="4" break="no"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="19" unit="character"/>vakīrtti-kṣemadatta-goṣṭhaka-varggapāla-piṅgala-śuṅkuka-kāla-<!-- 
daba: Lielukhine (naming no source) proposes Śivakīrtti for the partially lost name and says Banerji reads kṣamavanta, presumably for kṣemadatta. 
--><lb 
n="5"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="20" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">pa</unclear>viṣṇu-<unclear>deva</unclear>śarmma-viṣṇubhadra-khāsaka-rāmaka-gopāla-<!-- 
daba: Lielukhine says Banerji reads viṣyabhadra instead of viṣṇubhadra. 
--><lb 
n="6"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="18" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">sasu</unclear> śrībhadra-somapāla-rāmā<unclear cert="low">dyāḥ</unclear> grāmāṣṭa-kulādhikaraṇañ ca<!-- 
daba: Bhandarkar reads Rām-ādyāḥ(?); no way to tell if the question mark is meant just for the visarga or for more. Lielukhine (Sircar?) has rāmādyaka, also with a question mark. 
--><!-- 
daba: Lielukhine also has °karaṇaśca at the end. 
--><!-- 
daba: And while we're at it, Bhandarkar's sa(?) su(?) may represent two alternatives rather than two successive characters? I can't make out anything on the photo. 
--><lb 
n="7"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="15" unit="character"/>viṣṇu<unclear cert="low">nā</unclear> vijñāpitā Iha khādā<unclear cert="low">ṭa</unclear>pāra-viṣaye 'nuvr̥tta-maryyādā-sthi<unclear>ti</unclear>-<!-- 
daba: again, the ? after viṣṇunā may refer to more than just the nā. Lielukhine also has ṇā in brackets with a question mark, probably meaning that the original text may have ṇā. 
--><!-- 
daba: Lielukhine says Banerji read mahākhuṣāpāra instead of khādā(?ṭa)pāra. 
--><lb 
n="8"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="15" unit="character"/>nīvī-dharmma-kṣayeṇa labhya<unclear>te</unclear><!-- 
daba: Sircar reads nīvīdharmmākṣayeṇa rather than kṣayeṇa; Bhandarkar mentions his interpretation of kṣaya in his introduction of this inscr. 
--><!-- 
amwb : checking Sircar, he notes nīvīdharmmakṣayeṇa in his edition p.281 and suggests in brackets (kkra) and in note 3 dharmātkrayeṇa--></p>
<p><unclear>ta</unclear>d arhatha mamādyānenaiva kkrame<choice><sic>n</sic><corr>ṇ</corr></choice>a dā<unclear>tuṁ</unclear>
<lb 
n="9"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="14" unit="character"/>samety<unclear cert="low">ā</unclear>bhihitai<unclear cert="low">ḥ</unclear> sarvvam eva <unclear cert="low">jñā</unclear>kara-prative<unclear cert="low">śi</unclear>-kuṭumbibhir avasthāpya ka<!-- 
daba: Sircar restores Bhandarkar's (jñā?)kara as kṣetrakara. 
--><lb 
n="10" break="no"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="14" unit="character"/>ri <gap reason="illegible" precision="low" quantity="1" unit="character"/> kana <gap reason="illegible" precision="low" quantity="1" unit="character"/> yad ito <gap reason="illegible" precision="low" quantity="2" unit="character"/> <unclear>ta</unclear>d avadhr̥tam iti yatas tatheti pratipādya
<lb 
n="11"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="11" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="lost">aṣṭaka-na</supplied>vaka-nalā<unclear>bhyā</unclear>m apaviñchya kṣetra-kulya-vāpam ekaṁ dattaṁ tataḥ Āyuktaka-
<lb 
n="12"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="14" unit="character"/><unclear cert="low">bhrā</unclear>tr̥-kaṭaka-vāstavya-chandoga-brāhmaṇa-varāhasvāmino dattaṁ taddha<unclear cert="low">va</unclear><!-- 
amwb : Sircar p.281 note 7 suggests a restoration (probably of the beginning gap) : bhavadbhiḥ sarvairevānumodyānupālanīyaṃ
--><lb 
n="13" break="no"/><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="16" unit="character"/>bhūmyā dā<unclear>nākṣe</unclear>pe ca guṇāguṇam anucintya śarīra-k<unclear>ā</unclear>ñcanakasya ci<lb 
n="14" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">ra-cañcalatvaṁ</supplied> <gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="10" unit="character"/> <seg type="component" subtype="consonant"><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="component"/></seg>ā<!-- 
daba: the conjecture ra-cañcalatvaṁ is present in Sircar (probably his own?) and Agrawala, but not mentioned at all in Bhandarkar. 
--><!-- 
daba: ā after the lacuna is only found in Bhandarkar. I assume he saw a diacritical ā, not a full vowel. 
--></p>
<p><unclear>u</unclear>ktañ ca bhagavatā dvaipāyanena
</p>
<lg n="1" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">svadattām para-dattām vā</l>
<l n="b"><lb n="15"/><supplied reason="lost">yo hareta vasundharām</supplied></l>
<l n="c"><supplied reason="lost">sa viṣṭhāyāṁ kr̥mir bhūtvā</supplied></l>
<l n="d"><supplied reason="lost">pitr̥</supplied><unclear>bhiḥ</unclear> saha pacyate</l>
</lg>
<lg n="2" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">ṣaṣṭiṁ varṣa-sahasrā<choice><sic>n</sic><corr>ṇ</corr></choice>i</l>
<l n="b">svargge modati <unclear>bhū</unclear>midaḥ</l>
<l n="c"><lb n="16"/><supplied reason="lost">Ākṣeptā cānumantā ca</supplied></l>
<l n="d"><supplied reason="lost">tāny eva narake vaset</supplied></l>
</lg>
<lg n="3" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a"><unclear>pū</unclear>rvva-dattāṁ dvijātibhyo</l>
<l n="b">yatnād rakṣa yudhiṣṭhira</l>
<l n="c">mahīṁ <unclear>mahī</unclear><supplied reason="lost">matāñ cchreṣṭha</supplied></l>
<l n="d"><lb n="17"/><supplied reason="lost">dānāc chreyo 'nupālanam</supplied></l>
</lg>
<p><gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="10" unit="character"/>ya<unclear>ṁ</unclear> <unclear cert="low">su</unclear>śrībhadrena Utkīrṇṇaṁ sthambheśvaradāse<unclear>na</unclear> <gap reason="lost" precision="low" quantity="5" unit="character"/><!-- 
daba: Sircar restores the lacuna as likhitā paṭṭikeyaṁ amātyabhadreṇa (Bhadra as the name, not preceding the other -bhadra). He also says traces of ka are visible before ya(ṁ). Bhandarkar follows Basak in reading suśrībhadreṇa. 
--><!-- 
daba: Bhandarkar corrects the other name to stambheśvara-; Sircar reports Banerji as reading sthahṇeśvara (while Lielukhine reports Basak as reading so); Agrawala reads or conjectures Sthāṇvīśvara. 
--><!-- 
daba: note that the final 5 lost characters are only there if the line extends to the edge of the plate, but there isn't really anything else expected here 
--></p>
